title: [opt](nereids) compare literal not convert to legacy literal and fix ip literal compareTo always equals  0
body:
### What problem does this PR solve?

Issue Number: close #xxx

Related PR: #xxx

Problem Summary:

as #45181 mention, when sorting literals, toLegacyLiteral may cost a lot of time, so compare literal don't use toLegacyLiteral any more.

legacy literal may have an unknown behaviour  comparing two values with different data type.

for neredis literals,  different data type value compare will throw an exception,  it support valid compare with data types:
1. boolean vs boolean;
2. numeric vs numeric;
3. string like vs string like;
4. date like vs date like;
5. ipv4 vs ipv4;
6. ipv6 vs ipv6;
7. array vs array;
8. above data types vs null and max;

what's more, this pr also:
1. nereids literal remove implements Comparable<Literal>;
2. add a new interface ComparableLiteral,  and the above  type literals will implement it;
3. fix  ipv4 / ipv6 / map / struct compareTo always return 0;

title: [opt](mtmv) Optimize get available materialized view logic by reducing partition version comparison
body:
### What problem does this PR solve?

When checking available materializations, the system currently validates all partitions of the materialized view. In cases where it's a partitioned materialized view with a large number of partitions, this approach is inefficient. 

A better approach is to first identify the partitions required by the query, and then only validate the corresponding partitions in the materialized view. This PR implements this optimization.

Specifically:
- Before: Validates all partitions of the materialized view regardless of query needs
- After: Only validates the materialized view partitions that correspond to the partitions accessed by the query
- Benefits: Significantly reduces validation overhead for partitioned materialized views with many partitions

This optimization is particularly important for large-scale analytical databases where materialized views can have hundreds or thousands of partitions, but queries typically access only a subset of these partitions.

title: [opt](nereids) infer in-predicate from or-predicate
body:
### What problem does this PR solve?
previous verion has follow drawbacks
1. inferred some in-predicates, which cannot be pushed down to storage layer
2. it is easy to lead dead loop, because other expression rewrite rule may remove its flag in expression's mutableState

in order to solve above issues, we implemented a new version
first, it is a plan node level rule to avoid to be applied to the same expression repeatedly
second, we define replace mode and extract mode. if in replace mode, the original expression should be equivalent to the inferred in-pred, which is used for all plan node's expressions except filter.

for example, orig = "(a=1 and b=1) or (a=2 and c=2)" is equivalent to "a in (1, 2) and (a=1 and b=1) or (a=2 and c=2)".
orig is a filter condition, "a in (1, 2)" can be pushed down to storage layer, and this infer is useful. But if this is orig is an other join condition, this inferrence is useless. So in extract mode, "a in (1, 2)" is inferred, but in replace mode, it is not.
